13 (rotate by 13 places) is a simple letter substitution cipher. Our online=
 ROT13 encoder/decoder tool supports both letter and number encryption, fea=
turing both ROT13 encoder and ROT13 decoder functionalities.</div></div><di=
v><h3>How to use the ROT13 Encoder?</h3><div>Using the ROT13 encoder is sim=
ple: 1) Select 'Encode' mode; 2) Enter your text in the input field; 3) See=
 the ROT13 encoded result instantly. It preserves case sensitivity while ke=
eping non-letter characters unchanged.</div></div><div><h3>How to use the R=
OT13 Decoder?</h3><div>Using the ROT13 decoder is equally simple: 1) Select=
 'Decode' mode; 2) Input the ROT13 encoded text; 3) View the decoded origin=
al text. Due to ROT13's symmetry, encoding and decoding use the same algori=
thm.</div></div><div><h3>Why choose an online ROT13 tool?</h3><div>Our onli=
ne ROT13 encoder/decoder is completely free, requires no installation, and =
offers real-time conversion. Beyond standard ROT13 encryption, it supports =
ROT5 (number encryption) and ROT18 (combined), meeting various encoding/dec=
oding needs.</div></div><div><h3>How does ROT13 relate to Caesar cipher?</h=
3><div>ROT13 is a special case of the Caesar cipher. While Caesar cipher su=
pports letter shifts of 1-25 positions, ROT13 uses a fixed 13-position shif=
t. The number 13 is chosen as it's the middle value in a 26-letter alphabet=
, making encoding and decoding identical operations.</div></div><div><h3>Wh=
at encoding and decoding modes are supported?</h3><div>Our tool supports mu=
ltiple encoding/decoding modes: 1) ROT13 encoder/decoder (for letters); 2) =
ROT5 (for numbers); 3) ROT18 (letters and numbers); 4) Custom ROT shifts. E=
ach mode supports bidirectional conversion.</div></div><div><h3>How to hand=
le bulk text encoding/decoding?</h3><div>Our ROT13 encoder/decoder tool has=
 no text length limit and supports batch processing. You can copy and paste=
 large text blocks, and the tool will encode or decode in real-time with on=
e-click copy functionality.</div></div><div><h3>Does encoding affect text f=
ormatting?</h3><div>No. Our ROT13 encoder preserves the original case forma=
t, punctuation, spaces, and special characters. Only letters and numbers (d=
epending on the selected mode) are encoded.</div></div><div><h3>When should=
 I use ROT13?</h3><div>ROT13 encoding is commonly used for: 1) Hiding spoil=
ers; 2) Simple text obfuscation; 3) Online puzzle games; 4) Basic cryptogra=
phy education. While not suitable for sensitive information, it's practical=
 for casual text hiding.</div></div><div><h3>Why need custom ROT shifts?</h=
3><div>Beyond the standard ROT13 encoder/decoder, custom shifts allow you t=
o implement other Caesar cipher variants. Letters support 1-25 position shi=
fts, numbers support 1-9, providing flexibility in encoding.</div></div></d=
